Explain the difference between inheritance and composition in Python. When would you prefer one over the other?

✅ Answer (Straight to the point)
🔹 Inheritance
Represents “is-a” relationship
Child class inherits behavior from parent
Tight coupling → changes in parent can impact child
class Vehicle:
    def start(self):
        return "Vehicle started"

class Car(Vehicle):
    def drive(self):
        return "Car driving"

👉 Car is a Vehicle

🔹 Composition
Represents “has-a” relationship
One class contains another class as a component
Loose coupling → more flexible and maintainable
class Engine:
    def start(self):
        return "Engine started"

class Car:
    def __init__(self):
        self.engine = Engine()

    def drive(self):
        return self.engine.start() + " and Car driving"

👉 Car has an Engine

⚖️ When to Use What
Use Inheritance when:
Clear hierarchical relationship exists
Behavior is shared and stable
Example: Animal → Dog
Use Composition when:
You want flexibility and scalability
Components may change independently
Example: Car → Engine, Battery, GPS
⚠️ Reality (Important)
Overusing inheritance leads to:
Fragile design
Hard-to-maintain code

Modern design prefers:

Composition over inheritance

