Here is a clear, no-nonsense explanation of the answer, focusing on how it works internally and why it matters in real systems.

🧠 Core Concept

You were asked:

Difference between inheritance vs composition

This is not a syntax question.
It is a design decision question — poor choice here leads to rigid systems.

🔹 1. Inheritance — What actually happens
class Vehicle:
    def start(self):
        return "Vehicle started"

class Car(Vehicle):
    def drive(self):
        return "Car driving"
🔍 Internal behavior
Car inherits all methods from Vehicle
Python uses Method Resolution Order (MRO) to find methods

When you call:

car = Car()
car.start()

→ Python checks:

Car class
Vehicle class
⚠️ Problem
Car is tightly coupled to Vehicle
If Vehicle.start() changes → may break all child classes
📌 Key idea

Inheritance creates dependency at class level

🔹 2. Composition — What actually happens
class Engine:
    def start(self):
        return "Engine started"

class Car:
    def __init__(self):
        self.engine = Engine()

    def drive(self):
        return self.engine.start() + " and Car driving"
🔍 Internal behavior
Car does NOT inherit
It creates and uses an Engine object

When calling:

car.drive()

→ Car delegates work to Engine

📌 Key idea

Composition creates dependency at object level (runtime)

⚖️ Real Difference (Critical)
Factor	Inheritance	Composition
Relationship	IS-A	HAS-A
Coupling	Tight	Loose
Flexibility	Low	High
Change impact	High	Low
Runtime swap	❌ No	✅ Yes
🔥 Why Composition Wins (In Real Systems)
Problem with inheritance:

If tomorrow:

You want ElectricEngine
Or HybridEngine

With inheritance:

class ElectricCar(Car): ...
class HybridCar(Car): ...

👉 Explosion of classes

With composition:
class Car:
    def __init__(self, engine):
        self.engine = engine

Now:

Car(Engine())
Car(ElectricEngine())
Car(HybridEngine())

👉 No rewrite needed

💡 Deep Insight (What Interviewer Wants)

Good engineers understand:

Inheritance = compile-time rigidity
Composition = runtime flexibility

